Is it on? Okay.

00:03:48.770 --> 00:03:50.070
Good.

00:03:50.070 --> 00:03:51.370
Great.

00:03:51.370 --> 00:03:55.420
I'm going to have issues
with this thing here.

00:03:55.420 --> 00:03:58.290
Good morning, everyone,
and Congressman Aguilar.

00:03:58.290 --> 00:04:00.870
It is my great pleasure
to welcome you

00:04:00.870 --> 00:04:02.880
to the Library of
Congress today.

00:04:02.880 --> 00:04:04.740
We're so excited
that you're here.

00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:06.170
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar: Thank you
so much for having me, Jane.

00:04:06.170 --> 00:04:08.840
I really appreciate it and
thank you all for coming.

00:04:08.840 --> 00:04:12.300
Jane and I were just talking
that clearly this 10 a.m. block,

00:04:12.300 --> 00:04:14.970
there is a lot going
on here in Los Angeles.

00:04:14.970 --> 00:04:16.270
[Laughter].

00:04:16.270 --> 00:04:17.570
So thank you for choosing

00:04:17.570 --> 00:04:19.360
to spend a little
bit of time with us.

00:04:19.360 --> 00:04:20.660
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez: Yes.

00:04:20.660 --> 00:04:21.960
Thank you for choosing us.

00:04:21.960 --> 00:04:23.260
We're elated.

00:04:23.260 --> 00:04:24.930
Thank you for joining
us in celebration

00:04:24.930 --> 00:04:27.660
of Hispanic Heritage Month.

00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:30.080
And if you're ready, I have
some questions for you.

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:31.380
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar: Okay.

00:04:31.380 --> 00:04:32.680
I'm ready.

00:04:32.680 --> 00:04:33.980
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez: Alright.

00:04:33.980 --> 00:04:35.280
You are currently
the representative

00:04:35.280 --> 00:04:38.230
from California's 31st
Congressional District

00:04:38.230 --> 00:04:41.770
[inaudible] and the area
within the Inland Empire

00:04:41.770 --> 00:04:46.720
that encompasses San Bernardino,
portions of Rancho Cucamonga,

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:50.610
and of course, Redlands.

00:04:50.610 --> 00:04:53.590
As a former mayor of
Redlands and now Congressman

00:04:53.590 --> 00:04:55.930
to the region, how did you
begin your political career?

00:04:55.930 --> 00:04:58.150
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar: Well, I
began my political career

00:04:58.150 --> 00:05:00.860
by just being devoted
to service.

00:05:00.860 --> 00:05:03.860
Right. But the most difficult
part is kind of figuring

00:05:03.860 --> 00:05:06.100
out where you go from there.

00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:08.680
Quite honestly, I
was a staff member

00:05:08.680 --> 00:05:11.040
for an elected official
and I loved that.

00:05:11.040 --> 00:05:14.260
I thought that was exactly
where I wanted to be

00:05:14.260 --> 00:05:15.560
and who I wanted to be.

00:05:15.560 --> 00:05:17.190
I want to give my boss advice.

00:05:17.190 --> 00:05:20.420
I want to help make
recommendations and suggestions.

00:05:20.420 --> 00:05:22.180
I want to help make a
difference in the community.

00:05:22.180 --> 00:05:25.150
But no way, I don't want to give
any of those speeches or have

00:05:25.150 --> 00:05:27.040
to live with these
tough decisions.

00:05:27.040 --> 00:05:31.520
And then, you know, the
more you get, I guess,

00:05:31.520 --> 00:05:36.860
comfortable with in the
public policy forum,

00:05:36.860 --> 00:05:41.740
the more comfortable I became
you know making decisions,

00:05:41.740 --> 00:05:44.240
giving advice, having a
little bit more of an opinion

00:05:44.240 --> 00:05:46.150
on where we stood, the
direction we should take.

00:05:46.150 --> 00:05:50.820
And so, I started actually,
in the nonprofit world.

00:05:50.820 --> 00:05:54.410
I got involved and that would be
my lesson to the young people,

00:05:54.410 --> 00:05:57.060
is you know, just get
involved in your community.

00:05:57.060 --> 00:05:59.620
No matter what you're doing,

00:05:59.620 --> 00:06:03.520
no matter where you land it's
our responsibility to work

00:06:03.520 --> 00:06:07.250
to make our communities a better
place and there are hundreds

00:06:07.250 --> 00:06:08.550
and thousands of ways to do.

00:06:08.550 --> 00:06:12.040
Some very publicly and
then some were private.

00:06:12.040 --> 00:06:16.070
And so I got involved
with my community.

00:06:16.070 --> 00:06:17.370
I [inaudible] the board.

00:06:17.370 --> 00:06:18.670
I was President of
Board of Directors

00:06:18.670 --> 00:06:20.550
for Habitat for Humanity.

00:06:20.550 --> 00:06:21.850
I got to know members
of the community.

00:06:21.850 --> 00:06:23.150
I started talking about
housing, affordable housing.

00:06:23.150 --> 00:06:25.340
And then I got on the
Housing Commission

00:06:25.340 --> 00:06:27.060
in the city of Redlands.

00:06:27.060 --> 00:06:30.320
And that was a fun
outlet to dig into policy.

00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:32.610
And then a vacancy on
the City Council opened

00:06:32.610 --> 00:06:33.910
and I put my name in for that.

00:06:33.910 --> 00:06:36.880
And I said, actually one
of my good friends, I said,

00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:38.390
no I don't want to do that.

00:06:38.390 --> 00:06:40.300
I just got married,
baby on the way.

00:06:40.300 --> 00:06:44.040
This is not the right time.

00:06:44.040 --> 00:06:47.200
And he said, there's always
going to be an excuse.

00:06:47.200 --> 00:06:49.300
There's always going
to be a reason not

00:06:49.300 --> 00:06:51.370
to do something that's
difficult.

00:06:51.370 --> 00:06:53.820
But, you know, take the leap.

00:06:53.820 --> 00:06:55.830
We're all there with you.

00:06:55.830 --> 00:06:57.130
What's the worse
that can happen.

00:06:57.130 --> 00:06:58.930
I said, they say no.

00:06:58.930 --> 00:07:00.230
People say no.

00:07:00.230 --> 00:07:01.530
And he said that's fine,
in the grand scheme

00:07:01.530 --> 00:07:04.150
of things, you'll be okay.

00:07:04.150 --> 00:07:06.650
I was appointed to the City
Council as the youngest member

00:07:06.650 --> 00:07:11.310
of the City Council
in a hundred years.

00:07:11.310 --> 00:07:15.100
Became the youngest mayor
to the city after that.

00:07:15.100 --> 00:07:20.770
And it was just a lot
of fun to really dig

00:07:20.770 --> 00:07:23.900
into local government,
try to find solutions

00:07:23.900 --> 00:07:27.380
without party affiliation,
without any of that nonsense.

00:07:27.380 --> 00:07:29.320
You're just working with five
people for the people to try

00:07:29.320 --> 00:07:33.560
and make a difference
in your community.

00:07:33.560 --> 00:07:35.250
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez: So
how was the transition

00:07:35.250 --> 00:07:37.900
from mayor to congressman?

00:07:37.900 --> 00:07:40.340
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar: Well, you have
to build a lot more coalition.

00:07:40.340 --> 00:07:43.900
When there's four other
members of the City Council,

00:07:43.900 --> 00:07:46.760
you need three votes
to get something done.

00:07:46.760 --> 00:07:48.060
So I really just
needed two friends.

00:07:48.060 --> 00:07:49.360
[Laughter].

00:07:49.360 --> 00:07:53.040
But in most of the votes that
we had were actually a 4 to 1,

00:07:53.040 --> 00:07:58.170
5 to zero, and that's
the way we liked it.

00:07:58.170 --> 00:08:00.120
Here it's clearly
more difficult.

00:08:00.120 --> 00:08:03.160
It's more partisan
environment once you put a D

00:08:03.160 --> 00:08:04.720
or an R behind your name.

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:06.560
But I'll tell you there are ways

00:08:06.560 --> 00:08:10.250
to be successful,
even in that climate.

00:08:10.250 --> 00:08:13.720
Just like any relationship,
it just takes work.

00:08:13.720 --> 00:08:15.040
You have to build
those relationships.

00:08:15.040 --> 00:08:17.900
You have to reach out to your
colleagues across the aisle.

00:08:17.900 --> 00:08:21.620
You have to understand and be
self-aware that you're not going

00:08:21.620 --> 00:08:25.680
to agree with, you know,
everyone on every issue.

00:08:25.680 --> 00:08:28.850
But find the two or three,
or eight or ten issues

00:08:28.850 --> 00:08:31.940
that you do agree
with them on and try

00:08:31.940 --> 00:08:33.380
to [inaudible] the
needle and try

00:08:33.380 --> 00:08:35.200
to build a broader coalition.

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:38.520
I was proud to work with
Republican from South Texas,

00:08:38.520 --> 00:08:39.820
worked on immigration.

00:08:39.820 --> 00:08:44.230
We established a great
friendship as a result of that.

00:08:44.230 --> 00:08:45.700
I really enjoy spending
time with him.

00:08:45.700 --> 00:08:49.440
But we, you know, we're going
to disagree about the tax bill,

00:08:49.440 --> 00:08:52.600
we're going to disagree
about healthcare, probably.

00:08:52.600 --> 00:08:55.080
But we don't disagree
about immigration policy,

00:08:55.080 --> 00:08:56.400
making sure that
we have [inaudible]

00:08:56.400 --> 00:08:59.190
for so many young people.

00:08:59.190 --> 00:09:02.700
So those are the things that we
can do when we work together.

00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:04.000
It's hard in this environment.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:05.300
But it's possible.

00:09:05.300 --> 00:09:08.350
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez:
Okay, very good.

00:09:08.350 --> 00:09:11.870
How did your Mexican-American
heritage affect your decision

00:09:11.870 --> 00:09:15.530
to enter politics and how does
it now affect the policies

00:09:15.530 --> 00:09:18.000
and legislation that
you're passionate about?

00:09:20.070 --> 00:09:23.800
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar: My parents
and grandparents all grew

00:09:23.800 --> 00:09:26.360
up in the city of San
Bernardino, where I'm from.

00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:29.860
So walking around that city,
being around that community,

00:09:29.860 --> 00:09:34.400
we always had -- we always knew
our diversity was our strength.

00:09:34.400 --> 00:09:38.220
We always knew that that
sense of community kind

00:09:38.220 --> 00:09:39.570
of brought us together.

00:09:39.570 --> 00:09:42.830
And everyone of us was
afraid of our grandmother.

00:09:42.830 --> 00:09:44.130
[Laughter].

00:09:44.130 --> 00:09:49.070
So that's what really
united us as a community.

00:09:49.070 --> 00:09:53.590
But, I think, as you're growing
up what you find is, you know,

00:09:53.590 --> 00:09:56.320
the elected officials and
the people in the community,

00:09:56.320 --> 00:10:01.210
and the business owners, doesn't
always look like our community.

00:10:01.210 --> 00:10:07.210
So that's why that kind of
activism, and that discussion,

00:10:07.210 --> 00:10:10.290
you know, really kind
of [inaudible] I've got.

00:10:10.290 --> 00:10:12.040
This is what I want
for my community.

00:10:12.040 --> 00:10:13.880
I want them to be proud of
their elected officials.

00:10:13.880 --> 00:10:15.180
I want their elected officials

00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:17.900
to look the communities
in which we serve.

00:10:17.900 --> 00:10:21.730
And that's when I got a little
bit of the bug and wanting

00:10:21.730 --> 00:10:24.040
to give back at a higher level.

00:10:24.040 --> 00:10:28.390
And it's still to this
day the biggest source

00:10:28.390 --> 00:10:32.230
of pride is walking into high
schools and middle schools

00:10:32.230 --> 00:10:37.450
and talking to young people,
saying I went to this school,

00:10:37.450 --> 00:10:41.080
this is what I was doing when
I was your age, and this is --

00:10:41.080 --> 00:10:44.310
I didn't run for
student body leadership.

00:10:44.310 --> 00:10:45.610
I didn't do any of that.

00:10:45.610 --> 00:10:51.040
I was shy kid and usually
in the back, played sports,

00:10:51.040 --> 00:10:56.650
and loved hanging out with his
friends, and to kind of change

00:10:56.650 --> 00:11:01.660
and grow and to become a little
bit more community minded

00:11:01.660 --> 00:11:05.140
for what my surroundings were
has been a point of pride

00:11:05.140 --> 00:11:07.000
for me and my community.

00:11:08.520 --> 00:11:10.310
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez: Very good.

00:11:10.310 --> 00:11:12.210
So you are currently the Whip

00:11:12.210 --> 00:11:14.790
of the Congressional
Hispanic caucus.

00:11:14.790 --> 00:11:17.680
What was your pathway to
this leadership position

00:11:17.680 --> 00:11:19.610
and what does it mean to be part

00:11:19.610 --> 00:11:22.000
of the Congressional
Hispanic caucus?

00:11:23.120 --> 00:11:24.430
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar:
So there's 31 of us

00:11:24.430 --> 00:11:26.210
in the Congressional
Hispanic caucus,

00:11:26.210 --> 00:11:29.160
20 House members,
and two Senators.

00:11:29.160 --> 00:11:32.450
First Latino to be a
Congressional Hispanic caucus

00:11:32.450 --> 00:11:36.720
member is now among us,
Catherine Cortez Masto from --

00:11:36.720 --> 00:11:39.040
a Senator from Nevada.

00:11:39.040 --> 00:11:48.440
So it's been fun to
be part of that group

00:11:48.440 --> 00:11:49.740
because we share that identity.

00:11:49.740 --> 00:11:51.350
We share the communities
that we represent.

00:11:51.350 --> 00:11:54.220
But it's also forced me to think
through, okay, what's important

00:11:54.220 --> 00:11:58.160
to New Yorkers, what's important
to Floridians and Texans,

00:11:58.160 --> 00:11:59.460
New Mexicans, and Arizonians.

00:11:59.460 --> 00:12:01.040
We're all representing
similar communities.

00:12:01.040 --> 00:12:06.140
But also, you know,
Mexican-American is my heritage.

00:12:06.140 --> 00:12:09.470
But there are Puerto Ricans in
our caucus, there are members

00:12:09.470 --> 00:12:14.070
from Central America,
heritage from Central America.

00:12:14.070 --> 00:12:20.600
And so make sure we because
Latino is so inclusive

00:12:20.600 --> 00:12:25.180
in our communities making sure

00:12:25.180 --> 00:12:27.770
that we're truly
representing everyone,

00:12:27.770 --> 00:12:29.480
has been a focal
point of what we do.

00:12:29.480 --> 00:12:32.570
But it's allowed me to
have these member-to-member

00:12:32.570 --> 00:12:35.840
conversations about what's
important to your district,

00:12:35.840 --> 00:12:38.450
keeping in mind that not
every district is the same.

00:12:38.450 --> 00:12:45.350
There are members of the
Hispanic caucus who are Latino

00:12:45.350 --> 00:12:50.360
or Latina but maybe they don't
represent a very large Latino

00:12:50.360 --> 00:12:53.050
or Latina population and
so be mindful of that.

00:12:53.050 --> 00:12:56.510
Maybe their district is what
we would call a swing district,

00:12:56.510 --> 00:12:57.810
as well.

00:12:57.810 --> 00:13:00.730
And so knowing that each of
us represents a unique piece

00:13:00.730 --> 00:13:08.350
in the community and we all
come together and want to work

00:13:08.350 --> 00:13:10.880
with one another on
these shared issues is

00:13:10.880 --> 00:13:13.000
so incredibly fascinating
and important.

00:13:14.140 --> 00:13:15.440
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez: So
what does a Whip do?

00:13:16.040 --> 00:13:17.340
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar: Yes.

00:13:17.340 --> 00:13:20.050
So the Whip position
is a lot of fun

00:13:20.050 --> 00:13:25.040
and Steny Hoyer is the
Democratic Whip for our caucus.

00:13:25.040 --> 00:13:27.190
And so I've kind of
learned from Steny.

00:13:27.190 --> 00:13:30.470
But I will tell you the
single biggest thing

00:13:30.470 --> 00:13:33.900
for the Whip position
is knowing your members,

00:13:33.900 --> 00:13:38.040
knowing your colleagues and
having your finger on the pulse

00:13:38.040 --> 00:13:39.340
of what they want
to get accomplished.

00:13:39.340 --> 00:13:41.960
You have to be willing
to put the shared goals

00:13:41.960 --> 00:13:45.590
of the group before
your own personal goals.

00:13:45.590 --> 00:13:49.190
So the Whip position means
you need to know are there,

00:13:49.190 --> 00:13:51.710
in a group of 30,
are there 20 votes

00:13:51.710 --> 00:13:53.010
for what we're talking about?

00:13:53.010 --> 00:13:54.430
Are there 25 votes?

00:13:54.430 --> 00:13:56.510
Or are there only five?

00:13:56.510 --> 00:13:59.310
And maybe there are only five
but I'm one of those five.

00:13:59.310 --> 00:14:01.300
You have to have
the self-awareness,

00:14:01.300 --> 00:14:04.490
you have to have the leadership
to be able to say, I will go --

00:14:04.490 --> 00:14:07.420
we will go where our
caucus wants us to go.

00:14:07.420 --> 00:14:11.590
And that doesn't mean that you
can't continue to learn and grow

00:14:11.590 --> 00:14:14.680
and I always reserve the right
to try to convince my colleagues

00:14:14.680 --> 00:14:18.040
that I'm on the right side, even
if I'm in that smaller minority.

00:14:18.040 --> 00:14:22.210
But knowing where
your colleagues are

00:14:22.210 --> 00:14:26.570
and giving them space to make
those decisions, I think is one

00:14:26.570 --> 00:14:30.880
of the things from my
perspective is truly a tell-tale

00:14:30.880 --> 00:14:33.250
of Congressional leadership.

00:14:33.250 --> 00:14:35.650
You want to be able
to ask people

00:14:35.650 --> 00:14:37.830
where they are on an issue.

00:14:37.830 --> 00:14:40.490
What is -- how would your
district analyze this issue?

00:14:40.490 --> 00:14:43.960
Where do you come down on it?

00:14:43.960 --> 00:14:50.080
Well, this is what I would
do and this is how I talk

00:14:50.080 --> 00:14:52.080
about it in my community.

00:14:52.080 --> 00:14:55.560
I mean, if you think you
could get to a yes on this.

00:14:55.560 --> 00:14:57.470
But if they say no or I can't
or maybe, you have to know how

00:14:57.470 --> 00:14:59.610
to calibrate, how to continue
that educational discussion.

00:14:59.610 --> 00:15:01.420
And we see this, questions

00:15:01.420 --> 00:15:02.880
about the Congressional
Hispanic caucus

00:15:02.880 --> 00:15:05.670
but I see this is a
broader Democratic caucus

00:15:05.670 --> 00:15:06.970
that I worked in.

00:15:06.970 --> 00:15:09.200
There are a lot of our
colleagues who want

00:15:09.200 --> 00:15:13.520
to be helpful to the
Latino community.

00:15:13.520 --> 00:15:15.370
They want to do what's right.

00:15:15.370 --> 00:15:17.230
They just don't always
know what that means

00:15:17.230 --> 00:15:18.530
or how to talk about it.

00:15:18.530 --> 00:15:22.530
And they don't know our
community on issues.

00:15:22.530 --> 00:15:25.860
So I think a lot of this
is also our responsibility

00:15:25.860 --> 00:15:30.270
in the Hispanic caucus
to talk to our colleagues

00:15:30.270 --> 00:15:33.380
who don't know these
issues and to let them know

00:15:33.380 --> 00:15:38.510
where the community stands on
something and how we might talk

00:15:38.510 --> 00:15:41.850
about it or how you
might talk about it

00:15:41.850 --> 00:15:46.790
if you represented a district
that doesn't look like mine

00:15:46.790 --> 00:15:48.220
to give people the
background and the information

00:15:48.220 --> 00:15:49.520
to make an informed decision.

00:15:49.520 --> 00:15:52.250
But at the end of the day
we just have to respect

00:15:52.250 --> 00:15:53.830
where your colleagues
are on this

00:15:53.830 --> 00:16:00.050
and that's the beautiful part of
this institution is being able.

00:16:00.050 --> 00:16:04.070
I'm the only one that's here to
represent my entire community.

00:16:04.070 --> 00:16:07.880
And that is an incredibly
heavy weight that I have

00:16:07.880 --> 00:16:10.410
and each of us has that.

00:16:10.410 --> 00:16:13.250
So I trust that my colleagues
are making the right decision

00:16:13.250 --> 00:16:14.550
for their communities as well.

00:16:15.370 --> 00:16:17.560
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez: Very good.

00:16:17.560 --> 00:16:20.120
The Library of Congress
knows your office well.

00:16:20.120 --> 00:16:24.620
And your engagement with
our surplus book program.

00:16:24.620 --> 00:16:27.000
How would you define your
relationship to the library?

00:16:28.130 --> 00:16:30.650
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar: We were talking
about this a little earlier.

00:16:30.650 --> 00:16:34.010
I am just such a huge fan of the
Library of Congress and the work

00:16:34.010 --> 00:16:37.710
that everyone in this
institution does.

00:16:37.710 --> 00:16:39.490
But, I'll tell you,
a lot of work

00:16:39.490 --> 00:16:44.670
that they do is unknown,
under appreciated.

00:16:44.670 --> 00:16:48.960
And so, part of, I think, what
we need to do as members is

00:16:48.960 --> 00:16:51.220
to be advocates for
the institution.

00:16:51.220 --> 00:16:56.820
But to also let our colleagues
know about programs like this.

00:16:56.820 --> 00:16:59.850
That maybe aren't
as widely utilized.

00:16:59.850 --> 00:17:01.790
And to let them know
the services

00:17:01.790 --> 00:17:03.130
that the library can provide

00:17:03.130 --> 00:17:05.180
to our communities back
[inaudible] this is one

00:17:05.180 --> 00:17:08.200
that has been so
impressive to me.

00:17:08.200 --> 00:17:12.800
The fact that the library
is so generous with books

00:17:12.800 --> 00:17:14.100
for our local school districts.

00:17:14.100 --> 00:17:17.720
We worked with you to send
a little care package.

00:17:17.720 --> 00:17:21.730
There was a shooting in a
school in San Bernardino,

00:17:21.730 --> 00:17:28.150
where I'm from, and to be able
to send a care package of books

00:17:28.150 --> 00:17:32.160
to this school after that
event to hopefully, kind of,

00:17:32.160 --> 00:17:35.840
raise their spirits, give them
something new and something

00:17:35.840 --> 00:17:40.090
that they can tie them to
us was really powerful.

00:17:40.090 --> 00:17:45.010
And I always love that
it's stamped, it's courtesy

00:17:45.010 --> 00:17:46.310
of the Library of Congress.

00:17:46.310 --> 00:17:50.400
Because I want that young person
to also open that and say,

00:17:50.400 --> 00:17:51.700
what's the Library of Congress?

00:17:51.700 --> 00:17:53.010
And well, let's research that.

00:17:53.010 --> 00:17:54.310
Let's talk about that.

00:17:54.310 --> 00:17:56.930
Let's talk about
what that means.

00:17:56.930 --> 00:18:01.950
And to know that someone across
the country was generous enough

00:18:01.950 --> 00:18:06.350
to send them these books
is just means a lot to me

00:18:06.350 --> 00:18:09.300
and means a lot to
all of us members.

00:18:09.300 --> 00:18:12.420
But it was -- when
you come and visit us,

00:18:12.420 --> 00:18:14.410
in our Congressional offices,

00:18:14.410 --> 00:18:17.490
you probably told me
about this program.

00:18:17.490 --> 00:18:18.930
Probably told me 50 things
that you do but, you know,

00:18:18.930 --> 00:18:20.230
you just get into
town, and you're trying

00:18:20.230 --> 00:18:21.530
to build your staff
and it's very tough.

00:18:21.530 --> 00:18:25.280
So it was a couple of
other members saying, hey,

00:18:25.280 --> 00:18:26.580
do you do this program?

00:18:26.580 --> 00:18:28.600
You should make sure
your staff follows up

00:18:28.600 --> 00:18:30.330
and we're all doing this.

00:18:30.330 --> 00:18:32.590
So it's also a little bit
of that peer pressure.

00:18:32.590 --> 00:18:34.990
And so that's where it's
important for members

00:18:34.990 --> 00:18:37.630
to know the services that you
guys provide because I want

00:18:37.630 --> 00:18:41.630
to be a resource to those new
first-year members who are going

00:18:41.630 --> 00:18:42.930
to come in December
and say, hey,

00:18:42.930 --> 00:18:44.230
be sure you utilize
these services

00:18:44.230 --> 00:18:45.530
and you talk to the librarian.

00:18:46.930 --> 00:18:48.230
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez: Great, great.

00:18:48.230 --> 00:18:51.120
I hope you know about our
initial library services

00:18:51.120 --> 00:18:53.710
for the blind and
physically handicapped,

00:18:53.710 --> 00:18:56.110
and also our veteran's
history project, as well.

00:18:56.110 --> 00:18:57.410
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar: Yes, yes.

00:18:57.410 --> 00:18:58.710
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez:
Those are important.

00:18:58.710 --> 00:19:00.040
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar: Those
are important projects.

00:19:00.040 --> 00:19:02.490
And a little bit
about my history.

00:19:02.490 --> 00:19:05.820
My first job was working
for my grandfather

00:19:05.820 --> 00:19:08.520
who was a legally blind operator

00:19:08.520 --> 00:19:11.710
and there is actually a federal
program that trained him,

00:19:11.710 --> 00:19:13.190
called the Randolph-Sheppard
Act.

00:19:13.190 --> 00:19:16.280
And he served in the
Korean War, he came back,

00:19:16.280 --> 00:19:19.680
and he lost his eyesight
through a disease

00:19:19.680 --> 00:19:21.860
when my dad was in his teens.

00:19:21.860 --> 00:19:26.320
And my grandfather
had to be retrained.

00:19:26.320 --> 00:19:29.510
And he didn't know that
this program existed.

00:19:29.510 --> 00:19:30.810
A friend had told him and
my grandmother about it.

00:19:30.810 --> 00:19:32.110
And so he became a legally
blind owner-operator.

00:19:32.110 --> 00:19:34.860
So the programs that you
provide go far in line.

00:19:34.860 --> 00:19:41.110
And that's what I appreciate
so much about the library.

00:19:41.110 --> 00:19:42.840
And so much about our processes.

00:19:42.840 --> 00:19:45.920
Those investments to make sure
that everyone has a chance

00:19:45.920 --> 00:19:48.000
and an opportunity
that are so vital.

00:19:49.660 --> 00:19:50.960
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez: Thank you.

00:19:50.960 --> 00:19:53.840
What have been the legislative
goals of the Hispanic caucus

00:19:53.840 --> 00:19:57.000
for the 115th Congress and
what progress has been made?

00:19:59.060 --> 00:20:00.360
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar: Well, it feels
like we've been playing a lot

00:20:00.360 --> 00:20:01.660
of defense, obviously.

00:20:01.660 --> 00:20:05.380
And this isn't a
partisan discussion

00:20:05.380 --> 00:20:08.440
and I'll tell you it's
been incredibly frustrating

00:20:08.440 --> 00:20:15.420
because I do feel that the
administration is either

00:20:15.420 --> 00:20:17.230
planned, executed,
or fomented some

00:20:17.230 --> 00:20:18.530
of the most anti-immigrant
positions

00:20:18.530 --> 00:20:19.830
that we've seen in a long time.

00:20:19.830 --> 00:20:23.910
And so to try to dial that
back, try to push back

00:20:23.910 --> 00:20:27.600
with information, to try to
make sure that my colleagues

00:20:27.600 --> 00:20:31.040
and I stand up for the right
things and that we push back.

00:20:31.040 --> 00:20:32.780
You can see the administrations
policies

00:20:32.780 --> 00:20:34.550
when they're wrong
has been something

00:20:34.550 --> 00:20:38.330
that the Hispanic caucus
has tried to execute

00:20:38.330 --> 00:20:41.970
and put together a
plan on how we do that.

00:20:41.970 --> 00:20:44.470
It's been very public
that our plans,

00:20:44.470 --> 00:20:47.160
our focus are comprehensive
immigration reform.

00:20:47.160 --> 00:20:51.400
But we don't just
want to be the caucus

00:20:51.400 --> 00:20:56.840
about comprehensive immigration
reform when we have Latinos

00:20:56.840 --> 00:20:58.140
and Latinas who are in
incredible positions,

00:20:58.140 --> 00:20:59.440
in small business committees,

00:20:59.440 --> 00:21:00.740
energy and commerce committees
throughout this Congress.

00:21:00.740 --> 00:21:03.770
We have individuals who have
the skill set and working

00:21:03.770 --> 00:21:06.170
on these issues for decades.

00:21:06.170 --> 00:21:09.120
But this is clearly an
issue that is very personal

00:21:09.120 --> 00:21:10.420
to us and means a lot.

00:21:10.420 --> 00:21:14.080
And so to ensure that we
are making progress toward

00:21:14.080 --> 00:21:17.040
comprehensive immigration
reform has been a goal.

00:21:17.040 --> 00:21:19.630
And clearly the most important
thing right now is making sure

00:21:19.630 --> 00:21:26.670
that we have a permitted
fix for guideline to ensure

00:21:26.670 --> 00:21:31.870
that young people
who have DACA status.

00:21:31.870 --> 00:21:34.660
Those who are DACA eligible
have a path to citizenship,

00:21:34.660 --> 00:21:38.060
is something that we will
continue to fight for.

00:21:38.060 --> 00:21:39.380
That's the bill that I
authored and a bill that I plan

00:21:39.380 --> 00:21:41.000
to continue to be a part of
in the next Congress as well.

00:21:43.280 --> 00:21:45.390
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez: Recently
we've seen a renewed interest

00:21:45.390 --> 00:21:47.630
in politics and political
involvement

00:21:47.630 --> 00:21:49.850
from younger generations.

00:21:49.850 --> 00:21:52.980
What advice and words of
encouragement would you give

00:21:52.980 --> 00:21:55.860
to those who may be interested
in getting involved in local

00:21:55.860 --> 00:21:57.160
and national politics?

00:21:58.660 --> 00:21:59.960
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar: Do it.

00:21:59.960 --> 00:22:01.260
[Laughter].

00:22:01.260 --> 00:22:02.560
Jump in the water is fine.

00:22:02.560 --> 00:22:03.860
We need -- and here's
the important thing.

00:22:03.860 --> 00:22:10.000
We need young people to feel
committed to public service.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:15.500
And I want people to see members
of Congress conduct themselves

00:22:15.500 --> 00:22:18.040
in the right way, to work
in a bipartisan manner.

00:22:18.040 --> 00:22:21.030
I want people to see that and to
say, yes, I want to do that job.

00:22:21.030 --> 00:22:22.490
I want to serve my community.

00:22:22.490 --> 00:22:25.560
I don't want them to see
the food fight of, you know,

00:22:25.560 --> 00:22:27.880
what's on TV sometimes,
the back and forth,

00:22:27.880 --> 00:22:30.870
and to get discouraged and
say, I don't want to do that.

00:22:30.870 --> 00:22:35.190
You know, so, how we conduct
ourselves is also incredibly

00:22:35.190 --> 00:22:38.610
important because we
need another generation

00:22:38.610 --> 00:22:41.810
and continued generations
of young people to say,

00:22:41.810 --> 00:22:45.420
I want to serve, I want to make
a difference in my community.

00:22:45.420 --> 00:22:47.360
It may not always be
the most glamorous,

00:22:47.360 --> 00:22:49.560
it may not always
make the most money,

00:22:49.560 --> 00:22:53.460
but I can make an incredible
difference in my community.

00:22:53.460 --> 00:22:56.530
And so that's what
I hope that you --

00:22:56.530 --> 00:22:58.120
I hope that you get there.

00:22:58.120 --> 00:23:00.870
I hope that you find that
sense of community in place

00:23:00.870 --> 00:23:03.210
and want to give back.

00:23:03.210 --> 00:23:07.990
Like all of our parents and
grandparents to be able to make

00:23:07.990 --> 00:23:09.620
that community a better place

00:23:09.620 --> 00:23:11.080
and to leave it a little
bit better than we found it.

00:23:11.080 --> 00:23:15.620
That's getting more difficult
to say that we are doing that.

00:23:15.620 --> 00:23:18.320
And so we're going
to need policymakers

00:23:18.320 --> 00:23:21.750
and thought leaders
to help us get there.

00:23:21.750 --> 00:23:23.430
The only way we do
it is by making sure

00:23:23.430 --> 00:23:25.840
that the leadership tables
look like the communities

00:23:25.840 --> 00:23:31.920
in which we serve, to make sure
that everyone has an opportunity

00:23:31.920 --> 00:23:33.220
to give feedback and
help make a difference.

00:23:35.320 --> 00:23:37.370
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez: What does
Hispanic Heritage Month mean

00:23:37.370 --> 00:23:40.000
to you and how will your office
be celebrating this month?

00:23:42.040 --> 00:23:43.340
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar: We attend a
lot of events and celebrate

00:23:43.340 --> 00:23:44.640
and honor our heritage
and hone our culture.

00:23:44.640 --> 00:23:45.940
But we try to do
this year-round, too.

00:23:45.940 --> 00:23:47.240
Making sure that we honor
every culture in a community

00:23:47.240 --> 00:23:48.540
and to make sure that
they feel welcome.

00:23:48.540 --> 00:23:53.660
And that's the story of
our country is to make sure

00:23:53.660 --> 00:23:57.410
that immigrants are
welcomed and appreciated.

00:23:57.410 --> 00:24:05.800
And so, we want to make sure
that, especially this month,

00:24:05.800 --> 00:24:12.940
we're doing everything we
can to honor our communities

00:24:12.940 --> 00:24:16.190
and to make sure that we're
doing outreach, to make sure

00:24:16.190 --> 00:24:18.110
that everyone feels
that they have a place

00:24:18.110 --> 00:24:22.060
in our society, community.

00:24:22.060 --> 00:24:25.000
And to make sure that they
are loved and respected,

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:27.610
I feel is important
piece of what we can do

00:24:27.610 --> 00:24:29.000
and that's what our office
will continue to plan to do.

00:24:30.660 --> 00:24:32.060
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez: Great.

00:24:32.060 --> 00:24:34.460
Once again, thank you.

00:24:34.460 --> 00:24:36.940
Today is a reminder
that diversity is one

00:24:36.940 --> 00:24:39.430
of our country's
greatest strength.

00:24:39.430 --> 00:24:43.090
And Hispanic-Americans have
always been and will continue

00:24:43.090 --> 00:24:47.370
to be a key part of this rich
mosaic, which makes our country

00:24:47.370 --> 00:24:49.840
so unique and special.

00:24:49.840 --> 00:24:51.650
With that being said, maybe --

00:24:51.650 --> 00:24:54.080
let's check to see if
we have any questions

00:24:54.080 --> 00:24:56.720
from our gathering today.

00:24:56.720 --> 00:25:00.700
And we are delighted to have
our Gonzaga students here today.

00:25:00.700 --> 00:25:02.000
Thank you for coming.

00:25:03.040 --> 00:25:04.340
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar:
Thank you for coming.

00:25:04.340 --> 00:25:05.640
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez: Yes.

00:25:05.640 --> 00:25:06.940
So questions?

00:25:10.550 --> 00:25:11.850
Oh, come on.

