&gt;&gt; My name is Carlos
[inaudible].

00:25:19.920 --> 00:25:30.690
How do you feel that we as
Latinos do to overcome this gap

00:25:30.690 --> 00:25:34.160
that we see at [inaudible].

00:25:34.160 --> 00:25:36.090
You're at a position where
you can give us advice.

00:25:36.090 --> 00:25:42.990
So what's something you can
say to us that will push us

00:25:42.990 --> 00:25:44.430
and drive us to be
comfortable with that.

00:25:44.430 --> 00:25:45.730
Can you talk about that?

00:25:46.330 --> 00:25:47.630
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar: I think
what I would tell --

00:25:47.630 --> 00:25:49.020
thank you, Carlos,
I appreciate it.

00:25:49.020 --> 00:25:57.670
What I would tell you is if
you are just by virtue of being

00:25:57.670 --> 00:26:03.120
in those seats, you are doing
things that make your families

00:26:03.120 --> 00:26:04.970
and your community so proud.

00:26:04.970 --> 00:26:07.590
But the road needs
to go further.

00:26:07.590 --> 00:26:10.260
You need to continue to
make your families proud,

00:26:10.260 --> 00:26:12.060
to continue your education,

00:26:12.060 --> 00:26:18.290
and to continue being thoughtful
members of the community.

00:26:18.290 --> 00:26:20.350
That's how we make a difference.

00:26:20.350 --> 00:26:25.300
And what I would say is, you
know, many people are going

00:26:25.300 --> 00:26:27.820
to be the first in your
family to do a lot of things.

00:26:27.820 --> 00:26:29.120
I was.

00:26:29.120 --> 00:26:37.690
I was the first in my
family to go to college.

00:26:37.690 --> 00:26:41.220
I was the first in my family
-- this sounds very weird,

00:26:41.220 --> 00:26:42.520
but it was -- I was
in my mid-20s,

00:26:42.520 --> 00:26:43.820
and I was making more money

00:26:43.820 --> 00:26:45.120
than my parents were
making at the time.

00:26:45.120 --> 00:26:47.620
And there's a responsibility
that goes behind that.

00:26:47.620 --> 00:26:50.060
And it isn't about
dollar and cents.

00:26:50.060 --> 00:26:53.160
It's about the responsibility
to pay it forward.

00:26:53.160 --> 00:26:57.430
The responsibility to
help teach someone else,

00:26:57.430 --> 00:27:00.140
to help mentor someone
else to be successful.

00:27:00.140 --> 00:27:03.250
And so, as you go
through your schooling,

00:27:03.250 --> 00:27:06.920
as you go through your life
education, you're going

00:27:06.920 --> 00:27:10.710
to meet people who help you.

00:27:10.710 --> 00:27:15.150
And the most special thing is
the individuals who help you,

00:27:15.150 --> 00:27:16.780
who you learn later in life,

00:27:16.780 --> 00:27:22.050
there is no reason why
they needed to help me.

00:27:22.050 --> 00:27:26.040
They took an interest in me
and they saw something in you

00:27:26.040 --> 00:27:28.040
when you didn't see
it in yourself.

00:27:28.040 --> 00:27:30.760
And I have those
individuals in my life.

00:27:30.760 --> 00:27:35.140
And it's tough not to
get emotional about it.

00:27:35.140 --> 00:27:38.010
There were individuals who
believed in me much more

00:27:38.010 --> 00:27:41.050
than I believed in myself,
when I was in college

00:27:41.050 --> 00:27:43.130
and when I went into business.

00:27:43.130 --> 00:27:44.970
And I wouldn't be
here without them.

00:27:44.970 --> 00:27:50.180
But they meant the world to me.

00:27:50.180 --> 00:27:53.700
So make sure you just pause
and that you think about what

00:27:53.700 --> 00:27:57.570
that individual is
doing to help you.

00:27:57.570 --> 00:27:59.300
It could be giving
you political advice,

00:27:59.300 --> 00:28:01.310
it could be giving you
educational advice.

00:28:01.310 --> 00:28:07.040
It could be giving you an
opportunity to have a job.

00:28:07.040 --> 00:28:15.210
And so what that individual
has gone through, and every one

00:28:15.210 --> 00:28:18.930
of the individuals
that I can think of,

00:28:18.930 --> 00:28:26.440
three out of the four were
individuals in my community

00:28:26.440 --> 00:28:27.790
who were older, Caucasian,
and they saw something in me

00:28:27.790 --> 00:28:29.090
because they knew that our
communities were changing.

00:28:29.090 --> 00:28:32.590
And they knew that -- they felt
that I could make a difference.

00:28:32.590 --> 00:28:35.510
And they thought that
just by giving me a shot,

00:28:35.510 --> 00:28:39.350
giving me some advice,
that they could help.

00:28:39.350 --> 00:28:43.360
And so find people,
surround yourself with people

00:28:43.360 --> 00:28:45.190
who give you the
benefit of the doubt,

00:28:45.190 --> 00:28:46.490
who will help you along the way.

00:28:46.490 --> 00:28:51.360
Those are the individuals who
you want to interact with.

00:28:51.360 --> 00:28:54.410
Those are the people you're
going to learn the most from.

00:28:54.410 --> 00:29:00.070
And they're going to help open
doors for you and they're going

00:29:00.070 --> 00:29:01.370
to be your advocates and
throughout life you're going

00:29:01.370 --> 00:29:02.670
to have those individuals.

00:29:02.670 --> 00:29:06.640
And later when you reflect it's
going to mean the most to you.

00:29:06.640 --> 00:29:09.640
You may not know it when
you're in the middle of it

00:29:09.640 --> 00:29:12.440
but it's going to mean
the absolute most to you.

00:29:12.440 --> 00:29:16.180
And it's going to drive you
to make better decisions

00:29:16.180 --> 00:29:18.000
and to help open the door
for someone else behind you.

00:29:31.220 --> 00:29:32.520
&gt;&gt; Hi, I'm Justin [inaudible].

00:29:32.520 --> 00:29:36.630
What is the one experience
that you had

00:29:36.630 --> 00:29:41.050
that really has taught you
an important life lesson

00:29:41.050 --> 00:29:45.000
that you would like to pass on?

00:29:47.060 --> 00:29:51.240
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar: I'd say,
Justin, my first experience,

00:29:51.240 --> 00:29:54.690
I guess, as a community
organizer

00:29:54.690 --> 00:29:57.400
in politics kind
of taught me a lot.

00:29:57.400 --> 00:29:58.980
I was 10 years old.

00:29:58.980 --> 00:30:01.960
And the Exxon Valdez
spill happened.

00:30:01.960 --> 00:30:05.660
It was a big oil spill
that dominated the news.

00:30:05.660 --> 00:30:08.300
Way before you guys were born

00:30:08.300 --> 00:30:12.580
and now you're making
me feel old.

00:30:12.580 --> 00:30:13.880
[Laughter].

00:30:13.880 --> 00:30:15.180
I'm a pretty young guy.

00:30:15.180 --> 00:30:17.380
I saw these images on
the TV and I just --

00:30:17.380 --> 00:30:18.680
it drove me to want
to do something.

00:30:18.680 --> 00:30:20.030
I didn't know what to do.

00:30:20.030 --> 00:30:24.350
You see images of wildlife,
birds, or oil slick all over

00:30:24.350 --> 00:30:26.060
and the clean -- the
massive clean up efforts.

00:30:26.060 --> 00:30:28.950
And so, what I did was,
I was 10 years old,

00:30:28.950 --> 00:30:30.500
my parents were not
political at all.

00:30:30.500 --> 00:30:34.010
And they voted every
election, took us to the polls.

00:30:34.010 --> 00:30:36.030
They showed us the
importance of that.

00:30:36.030 --> 00:30:38.610
But they didn't talk
about who they voted for,

00:30:38.610 --> 00:30:40.870
we didn't have those
family conversations.

00:30:40.870 --> 00:30:44.000
And so I just started
writing letters.

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:49.250
I wrote a letter to the CEO of
Exxon, basically telling them

00:30:49.250 --> 00:30:53.480
that you guys messed up and
you need to pay for this.

00:30:53.480 --> 00:30:54.780
[Laughter].

00:30:54.780 --> 00:30:57.550
And you're a terrible company.

00:30:57.550 --> 00:30:58.850
Something like that.

00:30:58.850 --> 00:31:00.150
[Laughter].

00:31:00.150 --> 00:31:01.450
And so, I wrote it
and I felt okay.

00:31:01.450 --> 00:31:02.750
But I also felt that
I should share this.

00:31:02.750 --> 00:31:05.260
And so, I went door to
door with my neighbor.

00:31:05.260 --> 00:31:08.140
And I got people to sign
the petition, basically.

00:31:08.140 --> 00:31:10.190
Just a lined piece of paper

00:31:10.190 --> 00:31:12.550
and I said this is
the letter I wrote

00:31:12.550 --> 00:31:15.990
and I hope you share
this position with me

00:31:15.990 --> 00:31:17.750
and I hope you can sign
your name and I'm going

00:31:17.750 --> 00:31:19.070
to send it to the CEO.

00:31:19.070 --> 00:31:21.760
And my neighbors were like,
what the heck are you doing?

00:31:21.760 --> 00:31:23.060
[Laughter].

00:31:23.060 --> 00:31:29.370
But I think they all appreciated
that that's kind of who I was

00:31:29.370 --> 00:31:30.680
and it was a lesson,
and that was kind

00:31:30.680 --> 00:31:32.720
of my evolution and my growth.

00:31:32.720 --> 00:31:35.360
And what it taught me was, you
know, don't be afraid to get

00:31:35.360 --> 00:31:36.660
out of your comfort zone.

00:31:36.660 --> 00:31:39.120
You know, don't be afraid
to try something different

00:31:39.120 --> 00:31:41.150
that you haven't done.

00:31:41.150 --> 00:31:42.670
If it's who you are and
that's what you believe.

00:31:42.670 --> 00:31:43.970
It's not wrong.

00:31:43.970 --> 00:31:46.730
And so, I also think that your
generation is the most open

00:31:46.730 --> 00:31:52.100
about so many things that other
generations are not open to.

00:31:52.100 --> 00:31:59.430
So use that as a tool to
encourage other generations,

00:31:59.430 --> 00:32:01.960
my generation and others to
be more open about who you are

00:32:01.960 --> 00:32:07.280
and I think that's an
incredibly helpful.

00:32:07.280 --> 00:32:09.320
But I took it to school,
I wouldn't let any

00:32:09.320 --> 00:32:12.070
of my friends sign the petition.

00:32:12.070 --> 00:32:14.400
I said, you're not
18, you can't vote.

00:32:14.400 --> 00:32:15.700
You shouldn't sign this.

00:32:15.700 --> 00:32:18.910
But I went to all the teachers.

00:32:18.910 --> 00:32:20.210
[Laughter].

00:32:20.210 --> 00:32:21.510
And so, then I sent it.

00:32:21.510 --> 00:32:22.810
I don't think it was 40
or 50 signatures on it.

00:32:22.810 --> 00:32:24.330
My aunt convinced me to send
it certified mail so I knew,

00:32:24.330 --> 00:32:26.790
I got a little postcard
back that they received it.

00:32:26.790 --> 00:32:29.050
I kept that postcard for years.

00:32:29.050 --> 00:32:33.130
So, you know, that
was my first lesson

00:32:33.130 --> 00:32:35.440
in organizing, in leadership.

00:32:35.440 --> 00:32:38.400
And it taught me a lot
about just kind of getting

00:32:38.400 --> 00:32:39.700
out of your comfort zone.

00:32:39.700 --> 00:32:42.310
Being a shy kid doesn't mean
you can't make a difference

00:32:42.310 --> 00:32:43.610
or have your voice heard.

00:32:53.120 --> 00:32:57.010
We don't want to put all the
pressure on the Gonzaga kids.

00:32:57.010 --> 00:32:58.310
[Laughter].

00:32:59.120 --> 00:33:00.420
&gt;&gt; Representing [inaudible].

00:33:00.420 --> 00:33:05.290
I wanted to ask you about how
others see you in Congress?

00:33:05.290 --> 00:33:09.010
When there's this
message of America first

00:33:09.010 --> 00:33:10.310
and we're trying to
stifle diversity.

00:33:10.310 --> 00:33:12.430
What is the message that we can
bring forward to help others say

00:33:12.430 --> 00:33:19.470
that diversity is important and
how do you carry the narrative

00:33:19.470 --> 00:33:20.770
that your past [inaudible]
community

00:33:20.770 --> 00:33:22.070
over the majority of Americans?

00:33:22.070 --> 00:33:23.370
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar: Yes.

00:33:23.370 --> 00:33:24.670
That's a great question.

00:33:24.670 --> 00:33:28.160
And my response is every
community deserves a voice

00:33:28.160 --> 00:33:32.620
at the table and every
individual matter.

00:33:32.620 --> 00:33:37.970
I think it's generally accepted
among my colleagues is what we

00:33:37.970 --> 00:33:39.270
should be doing.

00:33:39.270 --> 00:33:43.450
I think the voices we hear and
some of this fervor we hear

00:33:43.450 --> 00:33:46.160
from the administration
is counter to that.

00:33:46.160 --> 00:33:52.050
But I find it -- I find that
having those conversations

00:33:52.050 --> 00:33:54.230
with my colleagues makes me
feel a little bit more at ease.

00:33:54.230 --> 00:33:57.710
And I'm talking about
both sides of the aisle.

00:33:57.710 --> 00:34:00.530
Folks understand that we
need to solve these issues.

00:34:00.530 --> 00:34:05.500
We might not always agree on how
to get there but I do have a lot

00:34:05.500 --> 00:34:08.380
of confidence in the
institution of Congress.

00:34:08.380 --> 00:34:11.550
I think that we can do
a lot more to ensure

00:34:11.550 --> 00:34:16.190
that we raise our voices
and we stand up to wrongs

00:34:16.190 --> 00:34:19.040
where we see them as a group.

00:34:19.040 --> 00:34:23.610
I do feel that we can do more.

00:34:23.610 --> 00:34:26.970
But I do think that we are
building coalitions in order

00:34:26.970 --> 00:34:28.270
to accomplish that goal.

00:34:28.270 --> 00:34:30.130
And that's what it's
going to take.

00:34:30.130 --> 00:34:31.860
Because not every
member, as I mentioned,

00:34:31.860 --> 00:34:35.980
is going to feel comforted
knowing what it took --

00:34:35.980 --> 00:34:39.060
what's important to
them in a community.

00:34:39.060 --> 00:34:41.210
So it's our job to
[inaudible] a segment

00:34:41.210 --> 00:34:45.980
of the community is just not as
large as mine or someone else's.

00:34:45.980 --> 00:34:50.360
And so my belief is that
they want to do right

00:34:50.360 --> 00:34:51.660
by [inaudible] districts.

00:34:51.660 --> 00:34:53.320
So we just have to show them.

00:34:53.320 --> 00:34:55.300
We just don't know how, yet.

00:34:55.300 --> 00:34:59.060
And so, it's on us
to show them how.

00:34:59.060 --> 00:35:02.540
To show them that the Latino
dream is the American dream.

00:35:02.540 --> 00:35:07.110
Better jobs, better wages,
all the affordable healthcare,

00:35:07.110 --> 00:35:10.300
access to education,
better life for our kids.

00:35:10.300 --> 00:35:12.840
That's the American dream.

00:35:12.840 --> 00:35:15.060
How is that -- how
are Latinos different?

00:35:15.060 --> 00:35:16.360
We're not.

00:35:16.360 --> 00:35:20.050
We want the exact same thing,
clean air, clean water.

00:35:20.050 --> 00:35:23.050
Those are things
that Latinos want.

00:35:23.050 --> 00:35:25.010
Not every Latino
wants comprehensive

00:35:25.010 --> 00:35:26.310
immigration reform.

00:35:26.310 --> 00:35:28.650
And we shouldn't act
as if that's the case.

00:35:28.650 --> 00:35:31.520
But everyone wants
a better community,

00:35:31.520 --> 00:35:33.040
better life their kids.

00:35:33.040 --> 00:35:36.580
So let's start with
that as the umbrella

00:35:36.580 --> 00:35:38.130
by which we can have
a conversation

00:35:38.130 --> 00:35:39.430
about all these other issues.

00:35:43.750 --> 00:35:46.340
&gt;&gt; I actually have
followed up question.

00:35:46.340 --> 00:35:48.140
You mentioned the DACA bill --

00:35:48.140 --> 00:36:20.500
[ Inaudible question ]

00:36:22.930 --> 00:36:24.230
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar:
That's a great question.

00:36:24.230 --> 00:36:29.760
And I think what we try to do
is you almost work backwards.

00:36:29.760 --> 00:36:31.360
It's what's the goal?

00:36:31.360 --> 00:36:33.050
Who do we want to help?

00:36:33.050 --> 00:36:36.620
And then let's make sure
that the legislation fits

00:36:36.620 --> 00:36:38.900
that -- fits that goal.

00:36:38.900 --> 00:36:43.210
So at first, quite honestly,
we had to decide in our piece

00:36:43.210 --> 00:36:46.090
of legislation who
we wanted to help.

00:36:46.090 --> 00:36:47.980
And then that would serve
as the basis for the --

00:36:47.980 --> 00:36:52.050
road map for the legislation
that we would develop.

00:36:52.050 --> 00:36:55.340
And clearly, and I
was very selfish,

00:36:55.340 --> 00:36:58.370
in all of my conversations
with my Republican colleagues.

00:36:58.370 --> 00:36:59.670
I would rather try
to help more people.

00:36:59.670 --> 00:37:06.090
And so that meant removing
barriers, removing age caps,

00:37:06.090 --> 00:37:10.530
that meant removing whether
someone actually has that status

00:37:10.530 --> 00:37:12.360
or whether they meet
the DACA criteria,

00:37:12.360 --> 00:37:14.120
what we call DACA eligible.

00:37:14.120 --> 00:37:16.080
I want them to --
I wanted to make it

00:37:16.080 --> 00:37:17.380
as expansive as possible.

00:37:17.380 --> 00:37:19.190
So my colleagues agreed.

00:37:19.190 --> 00:37:30.130
And so we were able to do
something that was a piece

00:37:30.130 --> 00:37:32.340
of legislation, that was more

00:37:32.340 --> 00:37:34.000
than 700,000 who
have DACA status.

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:35.300
It was two -- it would help 2
million eligible [inaudible]

00:37:35.300 --> 00:37:36.600
people receive the
path to citizenship.

00:37:36.600 --> 00:37:37.900
But you have to work backwards.

00:37:37.900 --> 00:37:41.740
And you have to, you know,
you have to work to ensure

00:37:41.740 --> 00:37:43.040
that we honor that humanity

00:37:43.040 --> 00:37:46.440
and that we're all
focused on the same goals.

00:37:46.440 --> 00:37:50.350
But you have to stop to
realize that not everyone

00:37:50.350 --> 00:37:53.930
in Congress reads these
pieces of legislation.

00:37:53.930 --> 00:37:57.410
And part of what we have to
do is we have to message it

00:37:57.410 --> 00:37:58.710
and we have to sell it.

00:37:58.710 --> 00:38:04.620
And so, honestly, we
told many individuals,

00:38:04.620 --> 00:38:07.040
look help us with this DACA fix.

00:38:07.040 --> 00:38:10.210
This will put folks on
the path to citizenship.

00:38:10.210 --> 00:38:12.130
And that was all they needed.

00:38:12.130 --> 00:38:14.050
We didn't even get into
the details about age caps.

00:38:14.050 --> 00:38:17.840
We didn't get into details
of you have a free pass

00:38:17.840 --> 00:38:19.950
to citizenship if you
work, go to school,

00:38:19.950 --> 00:38:21.510
if you've served the military.

00:38:21.510 --> 00:38:22.810
Some people wanted
more information

00:38:22.810 --> 00:38:24.110
and some people didn't.

00:38:24.110 --> 00:38:26.130
Some people this
is a different part

00:38:26.130 --> 00:38:30.100
and why I think it puts a
[inaudible] on relationships.

00:38:30.100 --> 00:38:34.520
And some people see the
messenger and say, okay, yes.

00:38:34.520 --> 00:38:37.040
I've got no -- I've worked
with you on things before.

00:38:37.040 --> 00:38:39.290
I know that when you
talk to my staff,

00:38:39.290 --> 00:38:46.630
but I know that you wouldn't
try to pitch me on something

00:38:46.630 --> 00:38:49.040
that wasn't right
for my community.

00:38:49.040 --> 00:38:53.910
And so, I think, that puts a
premium on the relationships

00:38:53.910 --> 00:38:55.210
that we have as members
to say, hey, you know,

00:38:55.210 --> 00:38:56.510
worked with me on stuff.

00:38:56.510 --> 00:38:57.810
Let's talk about this.

00:38:57.810 --> 00:38:59.110
Let me answer your
questions here.

00:38:59.110 --> 00:39:00.410
I want to pitch to
your staff on this.

00:39:00.410 --> 00:39:02.320
I want to go through
the details of this.

00:39:02.320 --> 00:39:08.500
Because oftentimes, what became
a hurdle were leadership offices

00:39:08.500 --> 00:39:11.120
here in Congress that
were giving members

00:39:11.120 --> 00:39:12.570
incorrect information.

00:39:12.570 --> 00:39:17.470
And so we had to debunk that.

00:39:17.470 --> 00:39:18.840
We had to put on out
our own topic points.

00:39:18.840 --> 00:39:21.510
We had to put out
frequently asked questions.

00:39:21.510 --> 00:39:27.070
And we had to really work
on a one-on-one basis

00:39:27.070 --> 00:39:31.520
with our colleagues
to educate them

00:39:31.520 --> 00:39:32.820
and tell them [inaudible]
piece of legislation.

00:39:32.820 --> 00:39:34.120
So making sure that the goal
was always the same for us.

00:39:34.120 --> 00:39:38.740
We have good partners and a good
piece of bipartisan legislation.

00:39:38.740 --> 00:39:41.410
And the goal is the
same for both of you.

00:39:41.410 --> 00:39:43.460
That's a great place to start.

00:39:43.460 --> 00:39:46.590
And so that's what we try to do.

00:39:46.590 --> 00:39:52.230
There are a lot of other
social and societal discussions

00:39:52.230 --> 00:39:54.780
that we could have
under that discussion.

00:39:54.780 --> 00:39:57.620
But honestly, we were
just so laser focused

00:39:57.620 --> 00:40:01.280
on how do we add
five co-sponsors?

00:40:01.280 --> 00:40:03.080
How do we get this
think on the floor?

00:40:03.080 --> 00:40:09.760
How do we improve this
coalition of the bill?

00:40:09.760 --> 00:40:16.480
You know, those were the
things that we were focused on,

00:40:16.480 --> 00:40:17.780
the very micro issues

00:40:17.780 --> 00:40:19.080
of [inaudible] something
that happens.

00:40:19.080 --> 00:40:20.380
And it was just an honor
to be part of that.

00:40:20.380 --> 00:40:21.680
I'm going to go down to
Texas and talk a little bit

00:40:21.680 --> 00:40:22.980
about the path forward
on immigration

00:40:22.980 --> 00:40:24.280
with Representative
Hurd this weekend.

00:40:24.280 --> 00:40:32.610
And I hope that we can continue
this bipartisan dialogue

00:40:32.610 --> 00:40:35.340
that needs to --
productive piece

00:40:35.340 --> 00:40:40.660
of legislation that
we can enact.

00:40:40.660 --> 00:40:43.930
And put on the President's
desk in the next Congress.

00:40:43.930 --> 00:40:49.020
Again, I want to thank you and
the Society for having me --

00:40:49.020 --> 00:40:50.340
I don't think it's time
to close yet but thank you

00:40:50.340 --> 00:40:51.640
so much for the invitation.

00:40:51.640 --> 00:40:52.940
It really means the world to
me to be able to share some

00:40:52.940 --> 00:40:54.240
of my experiences and talk
about my time in Congress.

