5

00:41:24.650 --> 00:41:27.000
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez: We
have someone here, too.

00:41:33.240 --> 00:41:35.250
&gt;&gt; Hi. My name is [inaudible].

00:41:35.250 --> 00:41:41.090
My question is Congressman,
there is talk

00:41:41.090 --> 00:41:45.130
about [inaudible] task force
American citizens along the

00:41:45.130 --> 00:41:46.800
[inaudible] Mexican borders.

00:41:46.800 --> 00:41:48.100
What are your thoughts
about this?

00:41:48.100 --> 00:41:49.400
Do you support it?

00:41:51.040 --> 00:41:53.690
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar:
No and this stems

00:41:53.690 --> 00:41:55.750
from a Washington Post
article that was recently put

00:41:55.750 --> 00:42:03.550
out where the Trump
administration is challenging

00:42:03.550 --> 00:42:06.800
citizenship, challenging
DACA immigration

00:42:06.800 --> 00:42:08.500
that individuals have
used to secure citizenship

00:42:08.500 --> 00:42:10.520
and legal permanent resident
status and citizenship.

00:42:10.520 --> 00:42:13.110
And look, I think -- and
this is what's difficult.

00:42:13.110 --> 00:42:15.070
I want we -- there's
a lot we need to learn

00:42:15.070 --> 00:42:18.130
about the questions they're
asking and what they're doing.

00:42:18.130 --> 00:42:22.690
I have signed on to some letters
to the Secretary to ask some

00:42:22.690 --> 00:42:26.500
of these questions, of USCIS
and of Homeland Security.

00:42:26.500 --> 00:42:29.290
And I look forward
to the responses.

00:42:29.290 --> 00:42:32.150
What I would say is, we
don't know enough yet.

00:42:32.150 --> 00:42:34.180
But what we have heard,
troubles [inaudible].

00:42:34.180 --> 00:42:40.470
And I feel like that statement
can apply to so many things here

00:42:40.470 --> 00:42:45.600
in the immigration space
from this administration.

00:42:45.600 --> 00:42:50.860
But I want to make decisions
that are based on fact,

00:42:50.860 --> 00:42:53.300
based on correct information.

00:42:53.300 --> 00:42:59.990
But if they are going to
individuals, if they are looking

00:42:59.990 --> 00:43:07.300
at documents and
challenging documents

00:43:07.300 --> 00:43:11.670
without basis then I have
a huge problem with that.

00:43:11.670 --> 00:43:15.750
If they are targeting border
communities and creating hurdles

00:43:15.750 --> 00:43:21.890
and roadblocks in order to
stifle someone's continued --

00:43:21.890 --> 00:43:25.330
LPR status or their
citizenship, then I'm going

00:43:25.330 --> 00:43:26.630
to have a huge problem
with their activities.

00:43:26.630 --> 00:43:28.350
So we need to make sure that
we get the right information.

00:43:28.350 --> 00:43:31.550
We get to know who
they are talking to.

00:43:31.550 --> 00:43:33.770
And what questions
they are asking.

00:43:33.770 --> 00:43:39.440
But I'll tell you, certainly
the appropriations committee

00:43:39.440 --> 00:43:40.740
and all that's questioned,
you know,

00:43:40.740 --> 00:43:42.040
what we were doing in committee.

00:43:42.040 --> 00:43:45.190
I passed an amendment that
surprised me, passed unanimously

00:43:45.190 --> 00:43:47.740
in the Homeland Security
subcommittee

00:43:47.740 --> 00:43:51.940
that prohibits the
administration

00:43:51.940 --> 00:43:56.800
from deporting anyone
with active, valid status.

00:43:56.800 --> 00:44:00.090
And active, valid status who
has served in the military.

00:44:00.090 --> 00:44:03.150
And I thought it was
going to be controversial

00:44:03.150 --> 00:44:04.690
and they accepted the amendment.

00:44:04.690 --> 00:44:06.450
We haven't passed that bill.

00:44:06.450 --> 00:44:09.140
That's one of the CR
that is carried forward.

00:44:09.140 --> 00:44:12.760
But we have our colleagues
on record that they are --

00:44:12.760 --> 00:44:18.070
that they want to pause
on any deportation

00:44:18.070 --> 00:44:19.370
of individuals with DACA status,

00:44:19.370 --> 00:44:21.180
which is a good place to start.

00:44:21.180 --> 00:44:26.270
[inaudible] other proposals,
like that you mentioned,

00:44:26.270 --> 00:44:29.650
that give me a great deal
of anxiety and heartburn

00:44:29.650 --> 00:44:33.530
because it's [inaudible]
to send a message

00:44:33.530 --> 00:44:37.260
to our community
that in some way,

00:44:37.260 --> 00:44:40.560
the administration is watching
and action you have taken

00:44:40.560 --> 00:44:44.040
in the past could
be brought back up.

00:44:44.040 --> 00:44:47.040
public charges in the
news, this week as well.

00:44:47.040 --> 00:44:51.170
So the fact that the
administration wants to try

00:44:51.170 --> 00:44:56.310
to prevent U.S. born citizens
from utilizing services

00:44:56.310 --> 00:44:58.190
for United States citizens,
whether that be SNAP,

00:44:58.190 --> 00:44:59.490
whether that's Headstart,

00:44:59.490 --> 00:45:05.100
or whether that's healthcare,
troubles me greatly.

00:45:05.100 --> 00:45:08.200
Because those are things,
I think, are out of bounds

00:45:08.200 --> 00:45:12.620
and those are things
that are in line

00:45:12.620 --> 00:45:14.550
with who we are as a community.

00:45:14.550 --> 00:45:16.930
Definitely in line
with the guidance

00:45:16.930 --> 00:45:18.420
that Congress has given.

00:45:18.420 --> 00:45:21.540
So we need to make sure that we
push back but we need to do it

00:45:21.540 --> 00:45:24.880
in a way that uses information
that we're gathering right now,

00:45:24.880 --> 00:45:27.210
the administration has been very
slow to give us those details.

00:45:27.210 --> 00:45:35.080
So I look forward to survey and
to getting more information.

00:45:35.080 --> 00:45:38.520
And if there is a change
in the next Congress,

00:45:38.520 --> 00:45:41.910
I would hope the
administration will be --

00:45:41.910 --> 00:45:43.750
our tools to encourage them

00:45:43.750 --> 00:45:47.100
to be more responsible
will be utilized.

00:45:47.100 --> 00:45:51.430
So we'll continue to ask these
questions and to make sure

00:45:51.430 --> 00:45:56.280
that they're treating everyone
correctly without harassment,

00:45:56.280 --> 00:45:57.580
without discrimination.

00:46:02.510 --> 00:46:28.000
[ Inaudible question ]

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:31.150
A little bit of what I said
before is to surround yourself

00:46:31.150 --> 00:46:32.740
with people who believe in you.

00:46:32.740 --> 00:46:34.040
Right?

00:46:34.040 --> 00:46:35.340
And once you have that
core group of friends

00:46:35.340 --> 00:46:38.990
and family members, it doesn't
matter what anybody else says.

00:46:38.990 --> 00:46:41.470
You can turn off that noise.

00:46:41.470 --> 00:46:46.150
But, look, my path is
probably similar to yours.

00:46:46.150 --> 00:46:50.370
I have people -- when I was
accepted to college, who said --

00:46:50.370 --> 00:46:55.330
I got a high school classmate
who was valedictorian

00:46:55.330 --> 00:46:59.510
and we went to the same
university and he said,

00:46:59.510 --> 00:47:04.160
that I got into the same
school he did because of I got

00:47:04.160 --> 00:47:07.270
to check a box that said
I was Hispanic or Latino.

00:47:07.270 --> 00:47:12.070
And in some way, in their minds,
the contributions and the work

00:47:12.070 --> 00:47:17.080
that I had done in high
school to get there

00:47:17.080 --> 00:47:20.370
and so there are going
to be individuals

00:47:20.370 --> 00:47:22.170
who minimize what you've
done to get to where you are.

00:47:22.170 --> 00:47:27.300
And the tough part of it is,
you know, pushing through that,

00:47:27.300 --> 00:47:33.440
knowing who you are, surrounding
yourself with friends who are

00:47:33.440 --> 00:47:35.430
in similar positions, making
sure you always have somebody

00:47:35.430 --> 00:47:36.730
to talk to about that.

00:47:36.730 --> 00:47:38.080
It may not always
be a family member

00:47:38.080 --> 00:47:41.620
because not every
family member is going

00:47:41.620 --> 00:47:47.250
to have those experiences.

00:47:47.250 --> 00:47:51.160
So making sure you have this
corporate friends around you

00:47:51.160 --> 00:47:54.910
who are looking out
for you is important.

00:47:54.910 --> 00:47:57.100
That will help you push
through that adversity.

00:47:57.100 --> 00:48:00.480
But don't every let
anyone minimize the work

00:48:00.480 --> 00:48:02.590
that you've done to
get to where you are.

00:48:02.590 --> 00:48:08.300
And now different people
handle things differently.

00:48:08.300 --> 00:48:11.060
I just kind of shrugged
and kind of laughed it off.

00:48:11.060 --> 00:48:14.290
And that's fine.

00:48:14.290 --> 00:48:19.100
I don't mind that, I'm a
pretty even keeled person.

00:48:19.100 --> 00:48:21.040
I'm not a screamer or yeller.

00:48:21.040 --> 00:48:24.560
But I was pretty
fired up about that.

00:48:24.560 --> 00:48:29.790
And it drove me to want to
do better and to want to --

00:48:29.790 --> 00:48:34.350
you know, it's always good,
it's always healthy to walk

00:48:34.350 --> 00:48:36.180
with a little chip
on your shoulder.

00:48:36.180 --> 00:48:39.410
To have self-awareness
to say, look,

00:48:39.410 --> 00:48:40.750
not everyone thinks
I can do this.

00:48:40.750 --> 00:48:42.760
But I think I can do this.

00:48:42.760 --> 00:48:45.830
And I think a little
bit of that is healthy.

00:48:45.830 --> 00:48:49.040
And so just know that
there are a lot of people

00:48:49.040 --> 00:48:51.580
that want you to succeed.

00:48:51.580 --> 00:48:54.550
And your community
needs you to succeed.

00:48:54.550 --> 00:48:57.490
And so that needs to always
be in your background.

00:48:57.490 --> 00:48:58.790
People you've never met.

00:48:58.790 --> 00:49:00.090
People you don't know.

00:49:00.090 --> 00:49:01.390
They want you to succeed.

00:49:01.390 --> 00:49:02.690
They want you to do well.

00:49:02.690 --> 00:49:07.430
And that will help you to kind
of push through any negativity

00:49:07.430 --> 00:49:08.730
that you may hear or see.

00:49:16.150 --> 00:49:18.230
&gt;&gt; My name is [inaudible]
Gonzaga.

00:49:18.230 --> 00:49:20.680
You mentioned that you were
the first in your family

00:49:20.680 --> 00:49:22.550
that had gone to college.

00:49:22.550 --> 00:49:24.280
My mother also was.

00:49:24.280 --> 00:49:26.080
Why do you --

00:49:26.080 --> 00:49:38.610
[ Inaudible question ]

00:49:38.610 --> 00:49:39.910
&gt;&gt; Pete Aguilar: Yes.

00:49:39.910 --> 00:49:43.540
So my advice is try everything.

00:49:43.540 --> 00:49:46.520
And that's why -- I love --

00:49:46.520 --> 00:49:50.220
I went to a liberal arts
college and I loved that.

00:49:50.220 --> 00:49:53.240
I went in thinking that I was
going to be a business guy.

00:49:53.240 --> 00:49:54.540
I loved business.

00:49:54.540 --> 00:49:57.040
It was kind of what
piqued my interest.

00:49:57.040 --> 00:49:58.590
And I kept taking these
government classes

00:49:58.590 --> 00:50:01.990
and finally a government's
professor said, hey,

00:50:01.990 --> 00:50:03.800
I'm going to have to kick you

00:50:03.800 --> 00:50:06.570
out of class unless
you change your major.

00:50:06.570 --> 00:50:07.870
[Laughter].

00:50:07.870 --> 00:50:09.310
And so you don't know what
you're truly going to love

00:50:09.310 --> 00:50:10.880
until you try a bunch
of these things.

00:50:10.880 --> 00:50:12.180
Right?

00:50:12.180 --> 00:50:15.450
That's why your parents let you
play musical instrument while

00:50:15.450 --> 00:50:17.720
you're doing sports,
while you're doing art.

00:50:17.720 --> 00:50:19.020
You just don't know.

00:50:19.020 --> 00:50:21.540
I mean, I've got a 12-year-old
and a 9-year-old right now.

00:50:21.540 --> 00:50:24.410
And they are driving
my wife and I crazy

00:50:24.410 --> 00:50:27.040
because they want
to try everything.

00:50:27.040 --> 00:50:29.200
And we want them to do that.

00:50:29.200 --> 00:50:30.860
We want them to find something

00:50:30.860 --> 00:50:33.390
that they're truly
passionate and love.

00:50:33.390 --> 00:50:39.010
I'll tell you, when you do that
and the light clicks, you know,

00:50:39.010 --> 00:50:40.750
your Mom's going
to be proud of you.

00:50:40.750 --> 00:50:45.880
You're going to feel like you're
ready to make the next step.

00:50:45.880 --> 00:50:51.180
So that's going to be a powerful
thing but don't feel the need

00:50:51.180 --> 00:50:56.420
to just do one or two things
or just try one or two things.

00:50:56.420 --> 00:51:02.290
You know, you guys are
going to be going to college

00:51:02.290 --> 00:51:03.840
and visiting schools and you
know, visit a couple of schools,

00:51:03.840 --> 00:51:05.430
visit some that you think isn't
necessarily, like, I don't know

00:51:05.430 --> 00:51:06.730
if that's right for me.

00:51:06.730 --> 00:51:09.840
But just get out of your
comfort zone and see.

00:51:09.840 --> 00:51:11.300
Walk around that campus and see

00:51:11.300 --> 00:51:14.080
if you can envision
yourself being there

00:51:14.080 --> 00:51:16.840
and contributing there.

00:51:16.840 --> 00:51:21.290
Those are things, I think that
will make your parents proud.

00:51:21.290 --> 00:51:24.560
And will lead to you
being successful.

00:51:24.560 --> 00:51:29.500
But, you know, get out
of your comfort zone

00:51:29.500 --> 00:51:35.050
and take some different classes
that you may not always like.

00:51:35.050 --> 00:51:36.430
I really think that will
help make you a more

00:51:36.430 --> 00:51:37.730
well-rounded student.

00:51:37.730 --> 00:51:41.110
It will help you focus
on what you truly like.

00:51:41.110 --> 00:51:42.800
I didn't know about how
much I disliked science

00:51:42.800 --> 00:51:44.770
until I took astronomy.

00:51:44.770 --> 00:51:46.090
And I said, this is hard.

00:51:46.090 --> 00:51:47.390
There's a lot of math.

00:51:47.390 --> 00:51:48.690
I thought I was going
to look at the stars.

00:51:48.690 --> 00:51:49.990
[Laughter].

00:51:49.990 --> 00:51:51.290
That was astronomy.

00:51:51.290 --> 00:51:55.050
Man. And so, I said, I'm
going back to government.

00:51:55.050 --> 00:51:58.610
I told my friends I picked
government over business,

00:51:58.610 --> 00:51:59.910
I doubled major in both.

00:51:59.910 --> 00:52:02.260
But I picked government
because I loved that I could --

00:52:02.260 --> 00:52:09.110
it only mattered if I could make
an argument in those classes.

00:52:09.110 --> 00:52:13.010
If I could make an argument it
didn't matter what my position

00:52:13.010 --> 00:52:14.570
was as long as I could prove it.

00:52:14.570 --> 00:52:16.620
In business and in math,
right, there's always answers.

00:52:16.620 --> 00:52:19.390
There's always answers
to these questions.

00:52:19.390 --> 00:52:23.100
But in government, let's
talk about these issues.

00:52:23.100 --> 00:52:24.620
Let's talk about 2nd amendment.

00:52:24.620 --> 00:52:26.370
Let's talk about
what this means.

00:52:26.370 --> 00:52:30.450
And if you can, you know, argue
it and believe it and back it

00:52:30.450 --> 00:52:33.160
up with facts and
citations, you're going

00:52:33.160 --> 00:52:34.900
to do well in those classes.

00:52:34.900 --> 00:52:36.200
I wanted to do that.

00:52:36.200 --> 00:52:38.220
I wanted to kind
of make my argument

00:52:38.220 --> 00:52:40.450
and to give my viewpoints.

00:52:40.450 --> 00:52:46.630
So be comfortable enough to
know that there are other things

00:52:46.630 --> 00:52:50.460
out there that you may not
even have taken classes

00:52:50.460 --> 00:52:52.250
on that you may grow to love
and be passionate about.

00:52:52.250 --> 00:52:57.590
Every one of us in professionals
has these types of stories.

00:52:57.590 --> 00:52:59.690
So just be prepared
that you're going

00:52:59.690 --> 00:53:01.050
to always continue to learn.

00:53:01.050 --> 00:53:03.670
I tried to -- in these
roles people will give you

00:53:03.670 --> 00:53:04.970
a microphone.

00:53:04.970 --> 00:53:06.930
They expect you to talk for,
you know, a long, long time.

00:53:06.930 --> 00:53:12.350
And I truly just love hearing
what other people think

00:53:12.350 --> 00:53:13.650
and listening and learning.

00:53:13.650 --> 00:53:17.000
Never stop, and the
librarians will tell you thin,

00:53:17.000 --> 00:53:21.300
this is a journey,
never stop learning.

00:53:21.300 --> 00:53:26.280
And just be aware enough
that even if something is

00:53:26.280 --> 00:53:29.940
where you truly love,
keep learning,

00:53:29.940 --> 00:53:31.240
keep reading, keep absorbing.

00:53:31.240 --> 00:53:32.540
And you're going to do --
you're going to be just fine.

00:53:32.540 --> 00:53:34.610
You're going to make
your Mom proud.

00:53:34.610 --> 00:53:37.100
But don't feel it's a huge
weight on your shoulders.

00:53:37.100 --> 00:53:39.520
Right. You're doing exactly
-- she may know sacrifices

00:53:39.520 --> 00:53:43.290
and she took those -- she made
those decisions so you could be

00:53:43.290 --> 00:53:45.930
in the chair that
you're in right now.

00:53:45.930 --> 00:53:47.800
Know that, acknowledge that.

00:53:47.800 --> 00:53:49.100
But that's not a weight.

00:53:49.100 --> 00:53:52.790
You should be proud of that.

00:53:52.790 --> 00:53:55.710
Your parents are going
to be proud of you

00:53:55.710 --> 00:53:58.210
in your next steps
and your journey.

00:53:58.210 --> 00:53:59.730
It's going to be a lot of fun.

00:53:59.730 --> 00:54:04.140
And we're all excited to
see what you guys do next.

00:54:04.140 --> 00:54:08.490
Having to honor your family and
your culture and your heritage.

00:54:08.490 --> 00:54:09.790
My grandmother told me two
things every time I would

00:54:09.790 --> 00:54:11.090
leave here.

00:54:11.090 --> 00:54:15.870
I could just go to the
store and come back.

00:54:15.870 --> 00:54:18.660
And she'd tell me two things.

00:54:18.660 --> 00:54:24.610
Right. Which are to be careful
and never forget who you are

00:54:24.610 --> 00:54:26.280
and where you came from.

00:54:26.280 --> 00:54:29.540
She tells me that and
I always think about it

00:54:29.540 --> 00:54:30.980
because I have an obligation
to family, to community

00:54:30.980 --> 00:54:32.280
to make this world a
little better place.

00:54:32.280 --> 00:54:33.580
That's what I want to do.

00:54:33.580 --> 00:54:34.880
And that's what you could do.

00:54:34.880 --> 00:54:36.180
I know that's what you could do.

